SIMPLE: peculiar
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Peculiar
<hw>Pe*cul"iar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>peculiaris</ets>, fr. <ets>peculium</ets> private property, akin to
<ets>pecunia</ets> money: cf. OF. <ets>peculier</ets>. See
<er>Pecuniary</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One's own; belonging solely
or especially to an individual; not possessed by others; of private,
personal, or characteristic possession and use; not owned in common or
in participation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And purify unto himself a <qex>peculiar</qex> people.</q>
<rj><qau>Titus ii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hymns . . . that Christianity hath <qex>peculiar</qex> unto
itself.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Particular; individual; special;
appropriate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While each <qex>peculiar</qex> power forgoes his wonted seat.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My fate is Juno's most <qex>peculiar</qex> care.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Unusual; singular; rare; strange; <as>as, the sky
had a <ex>peculiar</ex> appearance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Peculiar</er>, <er>Special</er>,
<er>Especial</er>.</syn> <usage> <xex>Peculiar</xex> is from the Roman
<xex>peculium</xex>, which was a thing emphatically and distinctively
one's own, and hence was dear. The former sense always belongs to
<xex>peculiar</xex> (as, a <xex>peculiar</xex> style,
<xex>peculiar</xex> manners, etc.), and usually so much of the latter as
to involve feelings of interest; as, <ex>peculiar</ex> care,
watchfulness, satisfaction, etc. Nothing of this kind belongs to
<xex>special</xex> and <xex>especial</xex>. They mark simply the
relation of <xex>species</xex> to <xex>genus</xex>, and denote that
there is something in this case more than ordinary; as, a
<xex>special</xex> act of Congress; <xex>especial</xex> pains,
etc.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beauty, which, either walking or asleep,⟦br⟧
Shot forth <qex>peculiar</qex> graces.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For naught so vile that on the earth doth live,⟦br⟧
But to the earth some <qex>special</qex> good doth give.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peculiar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Peculiar
<hw>Pe*cul"iar</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is
peculiar; a sole or exclusive property; a prerogative; a
characteristic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Revenge is . . . the <qex>peculiar</qex> of Heaven.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Canon Law)</fld> <def>A particular parish or
church which is exempt from the jurisdiction of the ordinary.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Court of Peculiars</b></col> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld>, <cd>a
branch of the Court of Arches having cognizance of the affairs of
peculiars.</cd> <au>Blackstone.</au> -- <col><b>Dean of
peculiars</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Dean</er>, 1.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peculiarity</ent>⟦br⟧
